thinking
**Evaluating argument handling**

In our runner, I see that `self.args.claude_bin` will handle a single string from argparse. It will be treated correctly even if it has spaces due to shell quoting. This means it's okay to pass it to the bash script as one argument. However, figuring out if there are extra arguments versus spaces in the path seems tricky. I wonder if I should just drop the `--claude-bin` flag. Maybe renaming the help to "binary/path" would clarify things.
thinking
**Adjusting wrapper behavior**

It seems okay to stick with the default since the likely use-case is `claude`. I should mention this, but to prevent inconsistent behavior, I could adjust `_run_claude` to use the direct path if `self.args.claude_bin` isn’t equal to `DEFAULT_CLAUDE_BIN`. This way, the wrapper would only apply to the default `claude`, which addresses the main Windows fix and keeps the custom command string problem from popping up. That feels like a better approach!
codex
I found one edge case worth hardening before I close this out: the wrapper only safely accepts a single executable/path for Claude, not an arbitrary multi-part command. I’m restricting wrapper usage to the default `claude` path on Windows and letting custom `--claude-bin` values fall back to direct execution.
